":{"about 1240–":"omkring 1240–Afdød","1240–Female":"1240–Afdød","1240–Male":"1240–Afdød","1264–Female":"1264–Afdød","1265–Male":"1265–Afdød","1267–Male":"1267–Afdød","1270–1300":"1270–1300","1270–Male":"1270–Afdød","1182–Male":"1182–Afdød","1210–Female":"1210–Afdød","1264":"1264","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1182":"1182","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1267":"1267","1300":"1300","Abt 1265":"omkring 1265","1453":"1453","1210":"1210","1265":"1265","about 1240":"omkring 1240","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Elton, Cheshire, England":"Elton, Cheshire, England","Broomham, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Ullenhall, Henley in Arden, Warwickshire, England":"Ullenhall, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Ashburnham, Sussex, England":"Ashburnham, Sussex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1240–":"circa 1240–Overleden","1240–Female":"1240–Overleden","1240–Male":"1240–Overleden","1264–Female":"1264–Overleden","1265–Male":"1265–Overleden","1267–Male":"1267–Overleden","1270–1300":"1270–1300","1270–Male":"1270–Overleden","1182–Male":"1182–Overleden","1210–Female":"1210–Overleden","1264":"1264","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1182":"1182","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1267":"1267","1300":"1300","Abt 1265":"circa 1265","1453":"1453","1210":"1210","1265":"1265","about 1240":"circa 1240","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Elton, Cheshire, England":"Elton, Cheshire, England","Broomham, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ullenhall, Henley in Arden, Warwickshire, England":"Ullenhall, Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ashburnham, Sussex, England":"Ashburnham, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1240–":"about 1240–Deceased","1240–Female":"1240–Deceased","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","1264–Female":"1264–Deceased","1265–Male":"1265–Deceased","1267–Male":"1267–Deceased","1270–1300":"1270–1300","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1182–Male":"1182–Deceased","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","1264":"1264","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1182":"1182","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1267":"1267","1300":"1300","Abt 1265":"about 1265","1453":"1453","1210":"1210","1265":"1265","about 1240":"about 1240","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Elton, Cheshire, England":"Elton, Cheshire, England","Broomham, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Ullenhall, Henley in Arden, Warwickshire, England":"Ullenhall, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Ashburnham, Sussex, England":"Ashburnham, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Elton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Elton (Berkshire, Cheshire, Derbyshire, Durham, Herefordshire, Huntingdonshire, Lancashire, and Nottinghamshire). The Eltons in Chesire, Derbyshire, and Durham are from Old English <i>ǣl</i> ‘eel’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. Elton in Berkshire is from the Old English female personal name <i>Æthelflǣd</i> (composed of the elements <i>æthel</i> ‘noble’ + <i>flǣd</i> ‘beauty’). Both Elton in Herefordshire and in Nottinghamshire are from the Old English personal name <i>Ella</i> + <i>tūn</i>. The Berkshire origin for the surname is especially well represented.","Norwegian: habitational name from a farm name in eastern Norway, in Old Norse <i>Elgjartún</i> ‘enclosed sacred place’ (or fenced in for <i>elg</i> ‘moose’?)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":19,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":50,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":75,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":88,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":97,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud de Elton was born about 1240, in Elton, Cheshire, England, her father, Thomas de Elton, was 60 and her mother, Mrs Thomas de Elton, was 32. She married Hammond Ashburnham in 1220, in Bromham, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters."},"et":{"about 1240–":"umbes 1240–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1264–Female":"1264–Surnud","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1267–Male":"1267–Surnud","1270–1300":"1270–1300","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1182–Male":"1182–Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1264":"1264","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1182":"1182","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1267":"1267","1300":"1300","Abt 1265":"umbes 1265","1453":"1453","1210":"1210","1265":"1265","about 1240":"umbes 1240","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Elton, Cheshire, England":"Elton, Cheshire, England","Broomham, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ullenha